title: For Sale/Trade:  Can we stop with the idiot pricing please?
postcontent:
Hey Armslisters,

I've about lost it with this site because ya'll can't seem to figure out what your weapons are worth. Probably most readers of this will be preached to like a choir, a bunch of the remainder will be insulted, and a few light bulbs will turn on. This is for the light bulb crew:

1) Your NIB gun isn't new if you took it home. If you aren't an FFL, then that gun is used. So - 90% of your original purchase price will sell it. Unless it is a rare, hard-to-find, or coveted item, you won't get your purchase price out of it because we will go down to our LGS and get it NIB ourselves.

2) Purchase price isn't the MSRP. We have all seen that the MSRP is $1100, but we paid $975 for whatever it is. So be aware that anyone can type the model you listed in Google and have a real price in 10 seconds.

3) Your Sightmark red dot and Simmons Wal-Mart scope do NOT add anything to the price. Just because you want to get rid of the garbage you bought or the fact that you spent a grand on an AR and then less than 10% on your glass - doesn't mean anyone else wants to be part of that. Either "throw it in free" or just keep it for your next bad decision. Give it your kid for his/her air rifle. But don't act like you are making a sweet package.

4) If I can buy it at my store for $20 or $800 or any other number, don't price yourself at the same or higher. I can't tell you how many ads for 33 Round Glock 9mm magazines I've responded to because they wanted $50-$60. The price is $34.95 for these in any store that is reputable. If you don't know a reputable store, write me. I'll send you their way. Your .22LR brick of 500 isn't worth $100. Your Beta drum isn't worth $400. Welcome to "The Democrats didn't pass the AWB and you should have put your money into stocks 2013." Buy up all the stuff you want - save it for a rainy day - but at least look outside to see if it is raining before you post your RIDICULOUS ads.

That being said, for the 10% of you that I would actually buy or sell a weapon to - thanks for posting. Carry daily, carry safely, and carry on.

SN

title: For Sale:  Smith and Wesson WW2 Victory Model .38spl C&R Eligible!
location: Leesburg, Sterling, Chantilly, Northern Virginia, Virginia
postcontent:
This is a beautiful Victory model Smith and Wesson, in the original wartime parkerized "battleship grey" finish. The manufacture on it appears to be 1944, though I can't verify that it was an issue gun. The Victory models are essential Model 10's before there was a model 10 - they are a K frame revolver, with a 6-shot cylinder, and a 4" pencil barrel, with half-lug. Like most Smith's, this is a double action revolver. This is .38 special ONLY - remember not to try .357 or .38+P in it!

This one has a case hardened trigger and hammer, and the hammer is factory rounded for holster draw. The sights are integral to the frame and barrel. Barrel is pinned, though not recessed. Finish has honest use, but is still VG - no dings or scratches. Barrel and cylinder are VG as well - clean, with no pitting, and well defined lands/grooves. The original plan walnut grips were replaced before I got it with a set of really incredible target K-frame grips - these will go on any of your other square or round butt Smiths, or will blissfully live on this gun. Note in particular the S&W medallion on the palm swell. 

This gun also has a really nice fitted Leather holster that goes with it, which will also accomodate any other 4" K-frame Smith. 

My only grief with the gun is that a previous owner (probably the same one that replaced the grips) lowered the front sight. The gun shoots high at 25 yards, and is dead on at 50. If you reload, I'd be happy to give you a reduced load that I built to let this one shoot at 25 yards accurately.

Always happy to respond with trades! Happy to ship to a C&R, or FFL, if you desire.

Please note - I will require a Virginia 21+ License and a Voter ID/CCW permit.

title: For Sale:  Complete BCG with Micro Slick
postcontent:
Cerakote™ Micro Slick is a dry-film lubricant that is able to withstand high temperatures and extreme pressures. The Micro Slick coating is able to lubricate, resist wear, and also act as an anti-seize agent while preventing galvanic corrosion or bonding of the metals.  Micro Slick is virtually unaffected by temperatures ranging between 800 and 1200 degrees Fahrenheit  When two adjoining surfaces are coated with Micro Slick it prevents surface-to-surface contact, which reduces friction and wear between the two surfaces. An example of this would be to coat a bolt carrier group on an AR 15 and the inside of the upper receiver. This combination would reduce the amount of friction between the parts and help the firearm to function more smoothly.

Micro Slick out-performs its competitors, such as Nickel Boron (NiB-X), Fail Zero, NP3, Titanium Nitride, etc. Because of this, Micro Slick is not only used on firearms, it is used on high performance vehicles as well, including vehicles in NASCAR.

Micro Slick is generally applied, but not limited, to internal, moving parts such as engine parts, bolts, bolt carrier groups, trigger groups, rails, etc. This product comes in a dark grey or black color only.

BCG specs:
158 Carpenter steel bolt
HPT/MPI tested 
grade 8 fasteners 
Staked gas key
Full auto profile carrier 
Made in the USA!
